datasets = {}
## Load all CSV from ZIP
with zipfile.ZipFile(zip_path, 'r') as zip_ref:
    for filename in zip_ref.namelist():
        if filename.endswith('.csv'):
            with zip_ref.open(filename) as file:
                datasets[filename.replace('.csv', '')] = pd.read_csv(file,low_memory=False)

# Calculate skewness Loan amount
loan_amount_skew = loans['Loan_Amount'].skew()
rounded_skew = round(loan_amount_skew, 3)

# Print skew value
print(f"Loan Amount Skewness: {rounded_skew}")

# Interpret the skewness based on your rules
if rounded_skew >= 1.0:
    print("Interpretation: Highly Right-Skewed")
elif rounded_skew > 0.5:
    print("Interpretation: Moderately Right-Skewed")
elif rounded_skew <= -1.0:
    print("Interpretation: Highly Left-Skewed")
elif rounded_skew < -0.5:
    print("Interpretation: Moderately Left-Skewed")
else:
    print("Interpretation: Symmetric")

# Calculate skewness EMI Amount

In[29]:
# Convert date columns
applications['Application_Date'] = pd.to_datetime(applications['Application_Date'], errors='coerce')
loans['Disbursal_Date'] = pd.to_datetime(loans['Disbursal_Date'], errors='coerce')

# Define previous financial year range (AprilMarch)
today = pd.Timestamp.today()
current_fy_start = pd.Timestamp(year=today.year if today.month >= 4 else today.year - 1, month=4, day=1)
previous_fy_start = current_fy_start - pd.DateOffset(years=1)
previous_fy_end = current_fy_start - pd.DateOffset(days=1)

# Filter data to previous FY
applications_prev_fy = applications[
    (applications['Application_Date'] >= previous_fy_start) &
    (applications['Application_Date'] <= previous_fy_end)
]
loans_prev_fy = loans[
    (loans['Disbursal_Date'] >= previous_fy_start) &
    (loans['Disbursal_Date'] <= previous_fy_end)
]

# Group by month
approvals_fy = applications_prev_fy['Application_Date'].dt.to_period('M').value_counts().sort_index()
disbursals_fy = loans_prev_fy.groupby(loans_prev_fy['Disbursal_Date'].dt.to_period('M'))['Loan_Amount'].sum().sort_index()

# Plotting
plt.figure(figsize=(14, 10))

# 1. Monthly Loan Approvals (Count)
plt.subplot(2, 1, 1)
sns.barplot(x=approvals_fy.index.astype(str), y=approvals_fy.values, color='skyblue')
plt.title("Monthly Loan Approvals - Previous FY")
plt.xlabel("Month")
plt.ylabel("Number of Approvals")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)

# 2. Monthly Loan Disbursements (Amount)
plt.subplot(2, 1, 2)
sns.barplot(x=disbursals_fy.index.astype(str), y=disbursals_fy.values, color='seagreen')
plt.title("Monthly Loan Disbursement Amount - Previous FY")
plt.xlabel("Month")
plt.ylabel("Total Disbursed Amount ()")
plt.xticks(rotation=45)

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

### Loan Disbursement Volume per Branch
#  Assign individual DataFrames
branches_df =  datasets['branches']
loans_df = datasets['loans']
defaults_df = datasets['defaults']

#  Calculate Default Rate per branch
branches_df['Default_Rate'] = branches_df['Delinquent_Loans'] / branches_df['Total_Active_Loans']

#Rank branches by key metric
ranking_df = branches_df.copy()
ranking_df['Rank_Disbursement'] = ranking_df['Loan_Disbursement_Amount'].rank(ascending=False)
ranking_df['Rank_Processing_Efficiency'] = ranking_df['Avg_Processing_Time'].rank(ascending=True)
ranking_df['Rank_Default_Rate'] = ranking_df['Default_Rate'].rank(ascending=True)  # lower is better

#Regional Performance Summary
region_summary = ranking_df.groupby('Region').agg({
    'Loan_Disbursement_Amount': 'sum',
    'Avg_Processing_Time': 'mean',
    'Delinquent_Loans': 'sum',
    'Total_Active_Loans': 'sum'
}).reset_index()
region_summary['Regional_Default_Rate'] = (
    region_summary['Delinquent_Loans'] / region_summary['Total_Active_Loans']
)
 #Display or Export
print("Branch Rankings:")
print(ranking_df[['Branch_ID', 'Branch_Name', 'Region', 'Rank_Disbursement',
                  'Rank_Processing_Efficiency', 'Rank_Default_Rate']].head())

print("\nRegional Performance Summary:")
print(region_summary)

customer_loans_df = pd.merge(customers_df, loans_df, on='Customer_ID', how='inner')

# Convert relevant fields
customer_loans_df['Annual_Income'] = pd.to_numeric(customer_loans_df['Annual_Income'], errors='coerce')
customer_loans_df['Credit_Score'] = pd.to_numeric(customer_loans_df['Credit_Score'], errors='coerce')

#  Define segmentation functions
def income_segment(income):
    if income >= 1000000:
        return 'High Income'
    elif income >= 500000:
        return 'Mid Income'
    else:
        return 'Low Income'

def credit_segment(score):
    if score >= 750:
        return 'Excellent'
    elif score >= 650:
        return 'Good'
    elif score >= 550:
        return 'Average'
    else:
        return 'Poor'

#  Apply segmentation
customer_loans_df['Income_Segment'] = customer_loans_df['Annual_Income'].apply(income_segment)
customer_loans_df['Credit_Segment'] = customer_loans_df['Credit_Score'].apply(credit_segment)

# Identify high-risk customers
high_risk_customers = customer_loans_df[
    (customer_loans_df['Credit_Score'] < 550) &
    (customer_loans_df['Loan_Status'] == 'Overdue')
]

# Identify high-value customers
high_value_customers = customer_loans_df[
    (customer_loans_df['Annual_Income'] >= 1000000) &
    (customer_loans_df['Credit_Score'] >= 750) &
    (customer_loans_df['Loan_Status'] == 'Active')
]

# S Repament behavior summary by segment
repayment_summary = customer_loans_df.groupby(
    ['Income_Segment', 'Credit_Segment', 'Loan_Status']
).agg({
    'Loan_ID': 'count',
    'EMI_Amount': 'mean',
    'Overdue_Amount': 'sum'
}).rename(columns={'Loan_ID': 'Loan_Count'}).reset_index()

# Step 9: Print or export
print("Repayment Behavior Summary:")
print(repayment_summary)

print("\nHigh-Risk Customers Sample:")
print(high_risk_customers[['Customer_ID', 'Full_Name', 'Annual_Income', 'Credit_Score', 'Loan_Status']].head())

print("\nHigh-Value Customers Sample:")
print(high_value_customers[['Customer_ID', 'Full_Name', 'Annual_Income', 'Credit_Score', 'Loan_Status']].head())

applications_df=datasets['applications']
loans_df = datasets['loans']

applications_df['Approval_Date'] = pd.to_datetime(applications_df['Approval_Date'], errors='coerce')

# Calculate processing time (in days)
applications_df['Processing_Time_Days'] = (applications_df['Approval_Date'] - applications_df['Application_Date']).dt.days

# Filter only approved applications with positive processing time
approved_apps = applications_df[
    (applications_df['Approval_Status'] == 'Approved') &
    (applications_df['Processing_Time_Days'] > 0)
].copy()

# Merge with loans to ensure valid Loan_IDs
merged = pd.merge(approved_apps, loans_df[['Loan_ID']], on='Loan_ID', how='inner')

# Calculate average processing time by loan purpose
avg_processing_by_purpose = (
    merged.groupby('Loan_Purpose')['Processing_Time_Days']
    .mean()
    .round(0)
    .reset_index()
    .sort_values(by='Processing_Time_Days', ascending=False)
)

# Display as table

# Analyze the number of defaults over time to identify patterns.
#  Load defaults data
defaults_df = datasets['defaults']

# Step 1: Convert dates
defaults_df['Default_Date'] = pd.to_datetime(defaults_df['Default_Date'], errors='coerce')
defaults_df['Year'] = defaults_df['Default_Date'].dt.year
defaults_df['Month'] = defaults_df['Default_Date'].dt.strftime('%b')  # abbreviated month name
defaults_df['Month_Num'] = defaults_df['Default_Date'].dt.month       # for sorting

# Get unique years for dropdown
year_options = sorted(defaults_df['Year'].dropna().unique().astype(int).tolist())

# Step 2: Define plotting function
def plot_defaults_by_year(year):
    df_year = defaults_df[defaults_df['Year'] == year]
    monthly = (
        df_year.groupby(['Month', 'Month_Num'])
        .size()
        .reset_index(name='Default_Count')
        .sort_values('Month_Num')
    )

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 5))
    sns.lineplot(data=monthly, x='Month', y='Default_Count', marker='o')
    plt.title(f'Monthly Default Trend - {year}')
    plt.xlabel('Month')
    plt.ylabel('Number of Defaults')
    plt.grid(True)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

# Step 3: Display dropdown
interact(plot_defaults_by_year, year=Dropdown(options=year_options, description='Select Year'))

# Calculate the average default amount for different loan purposes.
# Step 1: Load necessary datasets
defaults_df =  datasets['defaults']

# Step 2: Merge defaults with applications to get Loan_Purpose

# Step 3: Calculate average default amount by loan purpose
avg_default_by_purpose = (
    merged_df.groupby('Loan_Purpose')['Default_Amount']
    .mean()
    .reset_index()
    .sort_values(by='Default_Amount', ascending=False)
    .round(2)

# Compare default rates across customer income categories
customers_df =  datasets['customers']
defaults_df = datasets['defaults']
# Step 1: Create income categories using Annual_Income
bins = [0, 25000, 50000, 75000, 100000, float('inf')]
labels = ['<25K', '25K-50K', '50K-75K', '75K-1L', '>1L']
customers_df['Income_Category'] = pd.cut(customers_df['Annual_Income'], bins=bins, labels=labels, right=False)

# Step 2: Mark customers who defaulted
customers_df['Default_Flag'] = customers_df['Customer_ID'].isin(defaults_df['Customer_ID']).astype(int)

# Step 3: Group by income category and calculate default rate
income_default_summary = customers_df.groupby('Income_Category').agg(
    Total_Customers=('Customer_ID', 'count'),
    Defaults=('Default_Flag', 'sum')
).reset_index()
income_default_summary['Default_Rate (%)'] = (income_default_summary['Defaults'] / income_default_summary['Total_Customers'] * 100).round(2)

income_default_summary.sort_values(by='Default_Rate (%)', ascending=False)
